      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a question about my mortgage. i have a 30 year fixed at 6.5% and my monthly payment is about 2100. i was looking at my statement and it feels like even though i pay the same amount every month, almost none of it is actually hitting the principal in the beginning. can you explain why it's like that and maybe show me the difference in how much goes to interest vs principal around year 5 compared to year 25?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mortgages, especially those with a fixed rate, are often set up in a way that makes the interest a very large chunk of your early payments. This is because, at the start, the vast majority of your monthly payment is going towards covering the interest accrued on the large outstanding loan balance, not chipping away at the principal. You'll see that as the loan ages, the balance shrinks, and a bigger portion of that \\$2100 payment starts attacking the principal.\n\nHere’s the breakdown, though I can't give you exact figures without knowing the exact loan amount, but I can tell you how the *pattern* shifts.\n\n**Year 5 vs. Year 25 Comparison:**\n\n*   **Around Year 5:** You'll be in the thick of the early years. The interest portion of your payment will be significantly higher than the principal portion. Think of it like a small, quick-moving band of the principal being eaten by a huge, slow-moving horde of interest.\n*   **Around Year 25:** By this point, the principal balance has been significantly reduced. Consequently, the interest charged each month is much lower, meaning a much larger percentage of your \\$2",
      "source": "target",
